"Li J., Carlson B.E., Lacis A.A.","A study on the temporal and spatial variability of absorbing aerosols using total ozone mapping spectrometer and ozone monitoring instrument Aerosol Index data",2009,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","114","9",,"","",,,10.1029/2008JD011278,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-68249102781&partnerID=40&md5=f657f1acf36836299880d2fde5908689","Department of Earth and Environmental Sciences, Columbia University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States","Li, J., Department of Earth and Environmental Sciences, Columbia University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States, NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Carlson, B.E., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Lacis, A.A., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States","[1] Absorbing aerosols, especially mineral dust and black carbon, play key roles in climate change by absorbing solar radiation, heating the atmosphere, and contributing to global warming. In this paper, we first examine the consistency of the Aerosol Index (AI) product as measured by the Total Ozone Mapping Spectrometer (TOMS) and Ozone Monitoring Instrument (OMI) instruments and then analyze these AI data sets. to investigate the temporal and spatial variability of UV absorbing aerosols. In contrast to the trend in aerosol optical depth found in the advanced very high-resolution radiometer data, no obvious long-term trend in absorbing aerosols is observed from the time series of AI records. The comparison between the mean annual cycle in the two data sets shows that the cycles agree very well both globally and regionally, indicating a consistency between the AI products from TOMS and OMI. Varimax rotated Empirical Orthogonal Function (EOF) analysis of detrended, deseasonalized AI data proves to be successful in isolating major dust and biomass burning source regions, as well as dust transport. Finally, we find that large, individual events, such as the Kuwait oil fire and Australian smoke plum, are isolated in individual higher-order principal components. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Biomass; Carbon black; Dust; Fourier analysis; Global warming; Mining; Ozone; Spectrometry; Sun; Time series; Ultraviolet spectrometers; Absorbing aerosol; Aerosol index; Aerosol optical depths; Annual cycle; Biomass-burning; Black carbon; Data sets; Dust transport; Empirical orthogonal function analysis; High resolution; Higher order; Long-term trend; Mineral dust; Ozone monitoring instruments; Principal Components; Radiometer data; Source region; Temporal and spatial variability; Total ozone mapping spectrometer; UV absorbing aerosol; Atmospheric aerosols; atmospheric plume; atmospheric pollution; biomass burning; black carbon; climate change; data set; dust; optical depth; ozone; principal component analysis; radiometer; smoke; spatiotemporal analysis; spectrometer; time series; TOMS; Prunus domestica",,,,,,"Anuforom, A.C., Akeh, L.E., Okeke, P.N., Opara, F.E., Interannual variability and long term trend of UV-absorbing aerosols during Harmattan season in sub-Saharan West Africa (2007) Atmos. Environ, 41, pp. 1550-1559; Badarinath, K.V.S., Kharol, S.K., Chand, T.R.K., Use of satellite data to study the impact of forest fires over the northeast region of India (2007) IEEE Trans. Geosci. Remote Sens, 4, pp. 485-489; Camp, D.C., Roulston, M.S., Yung, Y.J., Temporal and spatial patterns of the interannual variability of total ozone in the tropics (2003) J. Geophys. Res, 108 (D20), p. 4643. , doi:10.1029/2001JD001504; Charlson, R.J., Schwartz, S.E., Hales, J.M., Cess, R.D., Coakley Jr., J.A., Hansen, J.E., Hoffman, D.J., Climate forcing by anthropogenic aerosols (1992) Sciences, 255, pp. 423-430; 